column3:
O2 - Suppose you are hired to develop a program that stores and manages student information at a university. Choose the best way to store data from two distinct categories: new and old students.
A.
- Use a single vector / list, where the odd indices contain information from the old and the even the new students;
- Veterans and freshmen must be represented by the same struct / class.
B.
- Use a single vector / list, where the odd indices contain information from the old and the even the new students;
- Veterans and freshmen must be represented by different structs / classes.
(C).
- Use two vectors / lists, one of which refers to old and the other to new students;
- Veterans and freshmen must be represented by different structs / classes.
D.
- Use two vectors / lists, one of which refers to old and the other to new students;
- Veterans and freshmen must be represented by strings.
E.
- Use a single vector / list, where the odd indices contain information from the old and the even the new students;
- Veterans and freshmen must be represented by strings.

column5:
O4 - Suppose you are hired to develop a program that stores and manages student information at a university. Choose the best way to implement adding and searching operations to retrieve students' data in a vector/list.
A.
- Add student: places a student in an occupied space of the vector / list;
- Search for student: search for a student at his / her age.
B.
- Add student: places a student in an occupied space of the vector / list;
- Search for student: search for a student by his / her date of birth.
(C).
- Add student: place a student in a free space in the vector / list;
- Search for student: search for a student by his / her enrollment number.
D.
- Add student: places a student in an occupied space of the vector / list;
- Search for student: search for a student by email.
E.
- Add student: place a student in a free space in the vector / list;
- Search for student: search for a student by his / her course.
